{"cursor":"3743","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nIn accounting and finance, '[[earnings]] before interest and taxes' ('EBIT'),\nalso called 'operating profit' or 'operating income' is a measure of a firm's\nprofit that excludes interest and income tax expenses. Bodie, Z., Kane, A. and Marcus, A. J.\nEssentials of Investments, McGraw Hill Irwin, 2004, p. 452. ISBN 0-07-251077-\n3 It is the difference between operating revenues and operating expenses.\nWhen a firm does not have non-operating income, then 'operating income' is\nsometimes used as a synonym for 'EBIT' and operating\nprofit. http://www.investorwords.com/3460/operating_income.html Operating\nincome definition\n\nEBIT = Revenue â Operating expenses (OPEX) + Non-operating income\n\nOperating income = Revenue â Operating expenses\n\nA professional investor contemplating a change to the capital structure of a\nfirm (e.g., through a leveraged buyout) first evaluates a firm's fundamental\nearnings potential (reflected by Earnings Before Interest, Taxes, Depreciation\nand Amortization EBITDA and EBIT), and then determines the optimal use of debt\nvs. equity.\n\nTo calculate EBIT, expenses (e.g., the cost of goods sold, selling and\nadministrative expenses) are subtracted from\nrevenues. http://www.investorwords.com/1631/EBIT.html EBIT definition\nProfit is later obtained by subtracting interest and taxes from the result.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\"|'Statement of Income â Example' (figures in\n|thousands) - colspan=\"2\"|'Revenue' -      Sales Revenue\n|align=\"right\"|$20,438 - colspan=\"2\"|'Operating Expenses' -\n|     Cost of goods sold align=\"right\"|$7,943 -\n|     Selling, general and administrative expenses\n|align=\"right\"|$8,172 -      Depreciation and amortization\n|align=\"right\"|$960 -      Other expenses align=\"right\"|$138\n|-          Total operating expenses\n|align=\"right\"|$17,213 - 'Operating income' align=\"right\"|'$3,225' -\n|     Non-operating income align=\"right\"|$130 -\n|bgcolor=\"yellow\"|'Earnings before Interest and Taxes (EBIT)' align=\"right\"\n|bgcolor=\"yellow\"|'$3,355' -      Financial income\n|align=\"right\"|$45 - 'Income before Interest Expense (IBIE)'\n|align=\"right\"|'$3,400' -      Financial expense\n|align=\"right\"|$190 - 'Earnings before income taxes' align=\"right\"|'$3,210' -\n|     Income taxes align=\"right\"|$1,027 - 'Net Income'\n|align=\"right\"|$2,183 }\n\n(Table info source: Bodie, Z., Kane, A. and Marcus, A. J. Essentials of\nInvestments, McGraw Hill Irwin, 2004, p. 452.)\n","linknr":196,"url":"Earnings_before_interest_and_taxes","recorded":1374546969,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Earnings_before_interest_and_taxes&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Earnings_before_interest_and_taxes&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Accountancy","/wiki/Accountant","/wiki/Accounting_period","/wiki/Accrual","/wiki/Bookkeeping","/wiki/Comparison_of_cash_and_accrual_methods_of_accounting","/wiki/Cash_flow_forecasting","/wiki/Chart_of_accounts","/wiki/Convergence_of_accounting_standards","/wiki/General_journal","/wiki/Special_journal","/wiki/Cost_of_goods_sold","/wiki/Trade_credit","/wiki/Debits_and_cr